mkstemp()/mkdtemp() seed their fallback filename RNG (used when rand_s() fails)
with _time32(NULL). On i386 the msvcrt import library aliases _time32 to the
plain, universally-present "time" export (msvcrt.def.in: `_time32 F_I386(== time)`),
so 32-bit binaries load everywhere. On x64 that alias is gone, so _time32 becomes
a hard IAT import of msvcrt.dll's literal _time32 export -- which only exists on
Vista and later. NT 5.2 (Windows Server 2003 / XP x64) ships an msvcrt.dll that
exports _time64 but NOT _time32, so any x64 program that pulls in mkstemp/mkdtemp
(e.g. anything using temp files) fails to load there with a missing-export error.

Switch the seed to _time64(NULL). mingw provides _time64 via the msvcrt_or_emu
glue (misc/_time64.c): it resolves msvcrt.dll's _time64 at runtime and falls back
to a GetSystemTime()/SystemTimeToFileTime() emulation when the export is absent,
so it is safe on every target and arch and never creates a static dependency on a
Vista+ symbol. The value is only used as entropy for a temp name, so truncating
the 64-bit result to unsigned int is harmless. Applied unconditionally.

diff --git a/mingw-w64-crt/misc/mkdtemp.c b/mingw-w64-crt/misc/mkdtemp.c
index 977aff2..d09a6e1 100644
--- a/mingw-w64-crt/misc/mkdtemp.c
+++ b/mingw-w64-crt/misc/mkdtemp.c
@@ -39,7 +39,7 @@ char *__cdecl mkdtemp (char *template_name)
     for (i = 0; i <= INT_MAX; i++) {
         for(j = index; j < len; j++) {
             if (rand_s(&r))
-                r = rand() ^ _time32(NULL);
+                r = rand() ^ (unsigned int) _time64 (NULL);
             template_name[j] = letters[r % 62];
         }
         ret = _mkdir(template_name);
